	abstract = {Text classification is an important and classical problem in natural language processing (NLP). Several studies have applied embedding from language models (ELMo) using deep learning methods for text-classification tasks. However, ELMo suffers to process the entire context of a sentence with bidirectional long short-term memory (BiLSTM) and the inference is slower compared to more efficient models. Compared to ELMo, bidirectional encoder representations from transformers (BERT) has bidirectional self-attention to understand the context of each word in a sentence by considering both the left and right contexts. Based on the fine-tuning technique, BERT has gained significant attention for text-classification tasks. In this study, we design and analyze three models based on BERT for the classification and recommendation of a substantial number of research papers. Specifically, we investigate a BERT-based convolutional neural network (CNN), a BERT-based BiLSTM network, and we propose a BERT-based CNN with BiLSTM combination model. To assess their performance, we conduct a comprehensive evaluation against ELMo-based models. The evaluation metrics are used include Accuracy, F1-score, ROC curve, and AUC score. Our experimental results demonstrate that the BERT-based models: BERT-based CNN, BERT-based BiLSTM, and the BERT-based CNN with BiLSTM outperform the ELMo-based models in all evaluation metrics for the tasks of research paper classification and recommendation. © (2025), (Korea Information Processing Society). All rights reserved.},
