	abstract = {The creation of automatic multiple-choice questions (MCQs) from unstructured text is necessary to develop scalable digital assessment systems and intelligent tutoring systems. While transformer-based question-generation models can produce linguistically fluent questions, these models often suffer from hallucinations, poor distractor construction, and lack adequate control over question difficulty. Therefore, the purpose of this study was to introduce a Hybrid LLM-Semantic Graph-based MCQ Generation Framework that utilized a combination of large language models (LLMs), semantic sentence embeddings, and graph-guided distractor selection. This framework provides an integrated solution to support the generation of semantically segmented questions, concepts extracted from relevant sentences, controlled question generation, and graph-constrained distractor ranking to enhance pedagogically valid MCQ generation. The experimental evaluation of the proposed Hybrid Framework demonstrates that it produces MCQs that result in higher BLEU scores (34.8) and BERTScores (0.91) than the transformer-only baselines, while also demonstrating significant improvement in distractor quality as measured through human evaluation. These findings demonstrate that the proposed hybrid framework enhances question relevance, semantic correctness, and educational alignment, thereby providing evidence that the proposed Hybrid Framework is effective.  © 2026 IEEE.},
