	pages = {1379 - 1384},
	doi = {10.1109/COMSNETS67989.2026.11418241},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105035389198?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Phishing attacks continue to be a major cybersecurity threat across both web and mobile ecosystems, leading to financial losses and compromised user data. Traditional detection systems relying on handcrafted features or single-source models often fail to generalize across diverse platforms and evolving attack strategies. To address these challenges, we propose Fusion-PhishGuard, an attention-enhanced, multi-branch deep learning framework designed for intelligent phishing detection across mobile and web environments. The framework performs multi-granular tokenization and integrates heterogeneous embedding paradigms - classical word embeddings (Word2Vec, FastText), Transformer encoders (BERT, RoBERTa, MiniBERT), and large language models (Qwen, Falcon) - to extract lexical, contextual, and semantic cues from URLs and mobile web links. A gated fusion-attention mechanism adaptively learns the importance of each embedding branch, while a BiLSTM-based sequential classifier captures ordered morphological and linguistic dependencies. Experiments conducted on two benchmark datasets, CatchPhish and PhishDump, demonstrate that FusionPhishGuard consistently outperforms baseline machine learning and deep learning models in accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. The proposed framework provides a unified, interpretable, and computationally efficient defense mechanism against evolving phishing attacks in modern mobile and web platforms. © 2026 IEEE.},
	type = {Conference paper},
