	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032191294?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Autism, clinically known as autism spectrum disorder (ASD), is a neurodevelopmental disorder. Autistic individuals tend to face more discrimination and challenges than other disabled people. This includes the social, educational, and employment spheres. Symptoms of ASD can be detected in children as young as toddlers. Early intervention can help them to overcome challenges whereas early detection of ASD is a new field of research that is being explored. The existing ASD research explored text and face images to detect autism that suffers from less accurate detection. This research proposes a novel approach named ASDToddler that considers a language model (LM) SBERT and a deep learning classifier BiLSTM to diagnose autism in toddlers. The proposed model considers binary and multiclass classification with a dataset that consists of toddlers descriptions. A notable accuracy of 0.97 and F1 score of 0.98 have been achieved compared to other traditional machine learning classifiers such as LR, SVM, and RF. The proposed model successfully created a model that takes input from the users in natural language and gives a reliable output.  © 2025 IEEE.},
