	abstract = {Pre-trained language models (PLMs) have rapidly evolved and show impressive performance in downstream tasks involving high-resource languages. However, these methods are insufficient in domain-specific tasks (e.g., medical entity recognition) involving low-resource languages (e.g., Mongolian). i. Mongolian is a low-resource language with complex word formation rules and a high degree of adhesion. ii. The clinical annotation data of Mongolian medicine are very scarce and difficult to annotate, leading to double-low-resource scenarios. Recently, prompt learning has shown good performance with PLMs, especially in small-sample scenarios. However, the impressive performance of prompt learning relies on the a priori knowledge of PLMs, and training a PLM for a vertical domain in such double-low-resource scenarios is difficult. Additionally, prompt design is a complex process requiring extensive expertise and considerable time for optimisation and refinement. In this paper, we propose a cross-lingual prompt and knowledge enhancement model based on named entity recognition for use with low-resource electronic medical records (CLPKB). First, word embeddings for source language prompts and data are mapped to target language vector space through a cross-lingual mapping matrix to reduce the spatial distance between the source and target languages. Then, cross-lingual soft prompts are used to transfer rich semantic features from the source to the target language to reduce the data dependence of the model. Meanwhile, external knowledge bases are utilised to enhance the contextual representations of the cross-lingual prompts to capture more domain-specific knowledge. The results show that our model improved by an average of 5.87% over the state-of-the-art baseline models. © 2025},
